                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d65">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">033.1110 Wallace, Henry A./110: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Scotten</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San José</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-03-18">March 18,
                            1943</date>.<lb/>[Received March 18—2:03 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>240. For Coordinator for Jamieson from Gaudet.<note n="13" xml:id="d65fn13">This
                        telegram was a message from one official to another of the office of the
                        Coordinator of Inter-American Affairs.</note> One greatest receptions ever
                    arranged for visiting dignitary now completed for Wallace who arriving plane
                    11:00 this morning. Cooperating with Government’s declaration national holiday
                    all merchants closing stores his honor, all schools closed and thousands young
                    school children will line streets welcome Wallace. Papers increased sizes order
                    carry full page ads, editorials, front page news stories on Wallace’s visit.
                    Taking on carnival spirits, city bedecked with canopy American, Costa Rican
                    flags. [Gaudet.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Scotten</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
